# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: darebase
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:darebase/american-handball] Games in which a ball is hit or thrown have been referenced as far back as Homer and ancient Egypt.
[src:darebase/american-handball] A game similar to handball was played by Northern and Central Americans from 1500 BC, most famously by the Aztecs as the Mesoamerican ballgame, but no references to a rebound game using a wall survive.
[src:darebase/american-handball] It is thought that these ancient games more closely resembled a form of hand tennis.
[src:darebase/american-handball] Further examples of similar games include the European-originated games of *Basque pelota* (or *Jai-alai*), Gaelic handball, *Valencian frontó*, International fronton and Eton fives.
[src:darebase/american-handball] References to similar games (then referred to as either "hand-tennis" and "hand-ball") have been found as early as 1287, when the Synod of Exeter banned the game due to the damage it caused to church buildings.
[src:darebase/american-handball] Other notable examples of wall ball games being banned include Robert Braybrooke, Bishop of London, who in 1385 prohibited the game.
[src:darebase/american-handball] Another recorded game of striking a ball against a wall using a hand was in Scotland in 1427, when King James I ordered a cellar window in his palace courtyard to be blocked up, as it was interfering with his game.
[src:darebase/american-handball] In Ireland, the earliest written record of a similar game is in the 1527 town statutes of Galway, which forbade the playing of ball games against the walls of the town.
[src:darebase/american-handball] The first depiction of an Irish form of handball does not appear until 1785.
[src:darebase/american-handball] The sport of handball in Ireland was eventually standardized as Gaelic handball.
[src:darebase/american-handball] By the mid-19th century, Australians were playing a similar game, which developed into the modern sport of Australian handball.
[src:darebase/american-handball] In *Treacherous Beauty*, by Mark Jacob and Stephen H.
[src:darebase/american-handball] Case, about the Arnold-Andre conspiracy, Major John André and General Sir Henry Clinton are said to have played a game called handball during the American Revolution.
[src:darebase/american-handball] The earliest record of the modern game in the United States mentions two handball courts in San Francisco in 1873.
[src:darebase/american-handball] The sport grew over the next few decades.
[src:darebase/american-handball] By the early 1900s, four-wall handball was well established and a one-wall game was developed in New York City by beach-goers who hit bald tennis balls with their hands against the sides of the wooden jetties that lined beaches.
[src:darebase/american-handball] This led to a rise in one-wall handball at New York beaches and by the 1930s, thousands of indoor and outdoor one-wall courts had been built throughout the city.
[src:darebase/american-handball] American handball is seen predominantly in parks, beaches, and high school yards in New York City, Lynbrook, New York, Philadelphia, Chicago and other large urban areas.
[src:darebase/american-handball] National championships in handball have been held annually in the United States since 1919.
[src:darebase/american-handball] These championships were organized by the Amateur Athletic Union (AAU) until 1950, when their control was transferred to the newly formed United States Handball Association (USHA).
[src:darebase/american-handball] For a complete list of champions, see List of American Handball Champions in the United States, and List of American Handball Women's Champions in the United States.
[src:darebase/american-handball] The sports of racquetball, squash, fives, four-wall and one-wall paddleball were heavily influenced by handball.
[src:darebase/american-handball] Four-wall and one-wall paddleball were created when people took up wooden paddles to play on handball courts.
[src:darebase/american-handball] Four-wall paddleball was invented in 1930 by Earl Riskey, a physical-education instructor at the University of Michigan, when he came up with the idea of using paddles to play on the school's handball courts.
[src:darebase/american-handball] Racquetball was invented in 1949 by Joseph Sobek in Greenwich, Connecticut, when he played handball using a strung racquet.
[src:darebase/american-handball] American handball is played on a walled court, with either a single (front) wall, three walls, or in a fully enclosed four-wall court; four-wall courts typically have a ceiling while three-wall courts may or may not.
[src:darebase/american-handball] The four-wall court is a rectangular box.
[src:darebase/american-handball] The front wall is 20 feet (6.1 m) square, and the side walls are 40 feet (12.2 m) long and 20 feet (6.1 m) high.
[src:darebase/american-handball] In the middle of the floor lies a short line, dividing the floor into two 20 feet (6.1 m) squares.
[src:darebase/american-handball] Also along the floor is the service line, which is 5 feet (1.5 m) in front of the short line.
[src:darebase/american-handball] The service zone is the area between these two lines.
[src:darebase/american-handball] The back wall of the court is usually 12 feet (3.7 m) high, with an above gallery for the referee, scorekeeper and spectators.
[src:darebase/american-handball] Some courts have a glass back wall and glass side walls to allow for better viewing.
[src:darebase/american-handball] In three-wall court handball, the court often has a front wall and two full side walls, or the front wall is flanked by two triangular wings.
[src:darebase/american-handball] Handball may be played as singles (two players against each other), doubles (two teams of two players), or "cutthroat" (three players rotating one against two).
[src:darebase/american-handball] In cutthroat handball, one server plays against two receivers, until they are "put out" (other terms include "down" or "side out").
[src:darebase/american-handball] Serves rotate in this way until one player wins by scoring either 7, 11, 15, or 21 points.
[src:darebase/american-handball] Should both teams reach a score 1 below the winning score, the game can be continued by "win-by-two" or "straight".
[src:darebase/american-handball] In "win-by-two", the winning score is increased by 2 points.
[src:darebase/american-handball] In 'straight', the score remains the same and cannot be pushed.
[src:darebase/american-handball] When a tie of 20 is reached in a 21-point match, a common decision is 'straight 25', where the winning score is set to 25 and cannot be changed.
[src:darebase/american-handball] The cutthroat mode of play is also known as "triangles".
[src:darebase/american-handball] The ball is served by one player standing in the service zone.
[src:darebase/american-handball] The server begins by dropping the ball to the floor of the service zone and striking it, after one bounce, with the hand or fist so that it hits the front wall.
[src:darebase/american-handball] The ball must hit the front wall first and it may then hit at most one side wall before the first bounce.
[src:darebase/american-handball] The served ball must then bounce on the floor past the short line but before reaching the back wall.
[src:darebase/american-handball] If the served ball lands in front of the short line, it is called a "short", while a serve that reaches the back wall without bouncing is called "long", and a serve that hits both side walls before hitting the floor is called a "3-wall".
[src:darebase/american-handball] These are all types of errors known as service faults.
[src:darebase/american-handball] After one service fault, the server will have only one serve remaining.
[src:darebase/american-handball] The server is "put out" by hitting two faults in a row and becomes the receiver, but if any serve hits the ceiling, floor, or a side wall *before* hitting the front wall, the server is out (no second serve allowed).
[src:darebase/american-handball] In doubles, the server's teammate has to stand in the service area with their back to a side wall in a service box, marked by a parallel line 18 inches (46 cm) from the side wall, until the ball passes the short line.
[src:darebase/american-handball] While the server has the ball, the receiver must stand at least 5 feet (1.5 m) behind the short line, indicated by dashed lines extending 6 inches (15 cm) from each side wall.
[src:darebase/american-handball] Once the ball is served, the receiver must hit the ball either directly ("on the fly") or after the first bounce.
[src:darebase/american-handball] A receiver choosing to take the serve on the fly, however, must first wait for the ball to cross the short line (the dashed line, in racquetball).
[src:darebase/american-handball] The ball can bounce off the floor twice.
[src:darebase/american-handball] Also, any player during a return may hit the ball off the floor before it touches the front wall.
[src:darebase/american-handball] The server then hits the ball on the rebound from the front wall, and play continues with the opponents alternately hitting the ball until one of them fails to make a legal return.
[src:darebase/american-handball] After the serve and return, the ball may be played from anywhere and may hit any number of walls, the ceiling, or a player so long as it hits the front wall before bouncing on the floor.
[src:darebase/american-handball] Players can "hinder" (block) their opponents from hitting the ball.
[src:darebase/american-handball] Servers failing to make a legal return is "put out" and becomes the receiver.
[src:darebase/american-handball] If the receiver fails to make the return, a point goes to the server, who continues to serve until "put out".
[src:darebase/american-handball] Only the server/serving team can score points.
[src:darebase/american-handball] The game goes to the player/team first to score 21 points.
[src:darebase/american-handball] A match goes to the player/team to win two out of three games; the third game goes to 11 points.
[src:darebase/american-handball] A three-wall handball court is an outside court with a front-wall, two side-walls (these may be "full" or "half"—half being a pair of sloping side-walls), and no back-wall in the play area.
[src:darebase/american-handball] It is played very much like an indoor four-wall court, only with the challenge of returning the ball without any back-wall rebound.
[src:darebase/american-handball] The long line at the forty-foot mark is considered out if the ball hits it when hitting the floor.
[src:darebase/american-handball] One-wall handball courts have a wall 20 feet (6.1 m) wide and 16 feet (4.9 m) high.
[src:darebase/american-handball] The court floor is 20 feet (6.1 m) wide and 34 feet (10.4 m) long.
[src:darebase/american-handball] When not played as part of tournament or league play, the one-wall game typically uses the bigger ball called "the big blue".
[src:darebase/american-handball] The main difference between one-wall handball and other versions is that the ball must always be played off the front wall.
[src:darebase/american-handball] One-wall handball can be watched by more people than a four-wall game.
[src:darebase/american-handball] The court is also cheaper to build, making this version of handball popular at gymnasiums and playgrounds.
[src:darebase/american-handball] In New York City alone, an estimated 2,299 public handball courts occupy the five boroughs.
[src:darebase/american-handball] A typical outfit includes protective gloves, sneakers, athletic shorts and goggles.
[src:darebase/american-handball] Eye protection is required in tournament handball, as the ball moves at high speeds and in close proximity to the players.
[src:darebase/american-handball] It is rarely used in "street" handball, however, where a softer "big blue" ball is usually used.
[src:darebase/american-handball] The black or blue rubber ball weighs 2.3 ounces (65 g) and is 1.875 inches (4.76 cm) in diameter (smaller, heavier, and more dense than a racquetball), is hit with a gloved hand (open palm, fingers, fist, back of hand) (informal games often do not include gloves).
[src:darebase/american-handball] A true handball is referred to as an "ace ball" or, in earlier days, "blackball".
[src:darebase/american-handball] A racquetball used to play handball is called a "big ball" or "big blue".
[src:darebase/american-handball] A small ball is hard, bounces higher and moves faster.
[src:darebase/american-handball] Types of small balls include the Red Ace (for men) and the White Ace (for women).
[src:darebase/american-handball] The Red Ace small ball is heavier than the White Ace small ball.
[src:darebase/american-handball] A big ball bounces slower and is softer and hollower than a small ball.
[src:darebase/american-handball] Four-wall games use the small ball almost exclusively.
[src:darebase/american-handball] Three-wall and one-wall games use both balls.
[src:darebase/american-handball] Both balls are used extensively in New York City, with formal tournaments for big ball, one example being NYC Big Blue.
[src:darebase/anglo-scottish-border] The **Anglo-Scottish border** is a land boundary that separates the countries of England and Scotland on the island of Great Britain.
[src:darebase/anglo-scottish-border] It runs for 96 miles (154 km) between Marshall Meadows Bay on the east coast and the Solway Firth in the west.
[src:darebase/anglo-scottish-border] The Firth of Forth was the border between the Picto-Gaelic Kingdom of Alba and the Anglian Kingdom of Northumbria in the early 10th century.
[src:darebase/anglo-scottish-border] It became the first Anglo-Scottish border with the annexation of Northumbria by Anglo-Saxon England in the mid-10th century.
[src:darebase/anglo-scottish-border] In 973, the Scottish king Kenneth II attended the English king Edgar the Peaceful at Edgar's council in Chester.
[src:darebase/anglo-scottish-border] After Kenneth had reportedly done homage, Edgar rewarded Kenneth by granting him Lothian.
[src:darebase/anglo-scottish-border] Despite this transaction, the control of Lothian was not finally settled and the region was taken by the Scots at the Battle of Carham in 1018 and the River Tweed became the *de facto* Anglo-Scottish border.
[src:darebase/anglo-scottish-border] The Solway–Tweed line was legally established in 1237 by the Treaty of York between England and Scotland.
[src:darebase/anglo-scottish-border] It remains the border today, with the exception of the Debatable Lands, north of Carlisle, and a small area around Berwick-upon-Tweed, which was taken by England in 1482.
[src:darebase/anglo-scottish-border] Berwick was not fully annexed into England until 1746, by the Wales and Berwick Act 1746.
[src:darebase/anglo-scottish-border] For centuries until the Union of the Crowns, the region on either side of the boundary was a lawless territory suffering from the repeated raids in each direction of the Border Reivers.
[src:darebase/anglo-scottish-border] The age of marriage under Scots law is 16, while it is 18 under English law.
[src:darebase/anglo-scottish-border] The border settlements of Gretna Green to the west, and Coldstream and Lamberton to the east, were convenient for elopers from England who wanted to marry under Scottish laws, and marry without publicity.
[src:darebase/anglo-scottish-border] The land border is near and roughly parallel to the 420 million-year-old Iapetus Suture.
[src:darebase/anglo-scottish-border] This expansion was driven by Norman, Breton, and Flemish forces encouraged by both Norman England and Alba, who dispossessed and colonised lands of Strathclyde, Galloway and Lothian to Northumbria, Cumberland (Cumbria), and Westmorland (Westmoringas).
[src:darebase/anglo-scottish-border] Previously, this broad region had been a complex mosaic of Brythonic, Anglian, Gaelic—including Norse and Norse-Gael communities and polities.
[src:darebase/anglo-scottish-border] The border country, historically known as the Scottish Marches, is the area on either side of the Anglo-Scottish border including parts of the modern council areas of Dumfries and Galloway and the Scottish Borders, and parts of the English counties of Cumbria and Northumberland.
[src:darebase/anglo-scottish-border] It is a hilly area, with the Scottish Southern Uplands to the north, and the Cheviot Hills forming the border between the two countries to the south.
[src:darebase/anglo-scottish-border] In 1333, during the Second War of Scottish Independence, Scotland was defeated at the Battle of Halidon Hill and Edward III occupied much of the borderlands.
[src:darebase/anglo-scottish-border] Edward declared Edward Balliol the new King of Scots, in exchange for much of southern Scotland and absolute supplication, but this was not recognised by the majority of the Scottish nobility who remained loyal to David II and conflict continued.
[src:darebase/anglo-scottish-border] By 1341, Perth and Edinburgh had been retaken by the Scots and Edward Balliol fled to England, effectively nullifying the supposed treaty.
[src:darebase/anglo-scottish-border] Edward would continue the war but would be unable to restore the puppet ruler Balliol to the throne and with the Treaty of Berwick (1357) Scottish independence was once again acknowledged with any pretence to territorial annexations dropped.
[src:darebase/anglo-scottish-border] A 16th-century Act of the Scottish Parliament talks about the chiefs of the border clans, and a late 17th-century statement by the Lord Advocate uses the terms "clan" and "family" interchangeably.
[src:darebase/anglo-scottish-border] Although Lowland aristocrats may have increasingly liked to refer to themselves as "families", the idea that the term "clan" should be used for Highland families alone is a 19th-century convention.
[src:darebase/anglo-scottish-border] This interchangeability, however, is conditional rather than automatic: Agnew and the Lord Lyon's own guidance both state that a clan or family is a legally recognised "noble incorporation" only once it has a chief recognised by the Lord Lyon.
[src:darebase/anglo-scottish-border] A name group without a recognised chief has no equivalent legal standing under either label.
[src:darebase/anglo-scottish-border] For centuries the Marches on either side of the boundary was an area of mixed allegiances, where families or clans switched which country or side they supported as suited their family interests at that time, and lawlessness abounded.
[src:darebase/anglo-scottish-border] Before the personal union of the two kingdoms under James, the border clans would switch allegiance between the Scottish and English crowns depending on what was most favourable for the members of the clan.
[src:darebase/anglo-scottish-border] For a time a powerful local clan dominated a region on the border between England and Scotland.
[src:darebase/anglo-scottish-border] It was known as the Debatable Lands and neither monarch's writ was heeded.
[src:darebase/anglo-scottish-border] Following the 1603 Union of the Crowns, King James VI & I decreed that the Borders should be renamed "the Middle Shires".
[src:darebase/anglo-scottish-border] In the same year the King placed George Home, 1st Earl of Dunbar in charge of the pacification of the borders.
[src:darebase/anglo-scottish-border] Courts were set up in the towns of the Middle Shires and known reivers were arrested.
[src:darebase/anglo-scottish-border] The more troublesome and lower classes were executed without trial; known as "Jeddart justice" (after the town of Jedburgh in Roxburghshire).
[src:darebase/anglo-scottish-border] Mass hanging soon became a common occurrence.
[src:darebase/anglo-scottish-border] In 1605 he established a joint commission of ten members, drawn equally from Scotland and England, to bring law and order to the region.
[src:darebase/anglo-scottish-border] This was aided by statutes in 1606 and 1609, first to repeal hostile laws on both sides of the border, and then to more easily prosecute cross-border raiders.
[src:darebase/anglo-scottish-border] Reivers could no longer escape justice by crossing from England to Scotland or vice versa.
[src:darebase/anglo-scottish-border] The rough-and-ready Border Laws were abolished and the folk of the middle shires found they had to obey the law of the land like all other subjects.
[src:darebase/anglo-scottish-border] In 1607 James felt he could boast that "the Middle Shires" had "become the navel or umbilic of both kingdoms, planted and peopled with civility and riches".
[src:darebase/anglo-scottish-border] After ten years King James had succeeded; the Middle Shires had been brought under central law and order.
[src:darebase/anglo-scottish-border] By the early 1620s the Borders were so peaceful that the Crown was able to scale down its operations.
[src:darebase/anglo-scottish-border] Despite these improvements, the Joint Commission continued its work, and as late as 25 September 1641 under King Charles I, Sir Richard Graham, a local laird and English MP, was petitioning the Parliament of Scotland "for regulating the disorders in the borders".
[src:darebase/anglo-scottish-border] Conditions along the border generally deteriorated during the Commonwealth and Protectorate periods, with the development of Moss-trooper raiders.
[src:darebase/anglo-scottish-border] Following the Restoration, ongoing border lawlessness was dealt with by reviving former legislation, renewed continually in eleven subsequent acts, for periods ranging from five to eleven years, up until the late 1750s.
[src:darebase/anglo-scottish-border] The Debatable Lands lay between Scotland and England to the north of Carlisle, the largest population centre being Canonbie.
[src:darebase/anglo-scottish-border] For over three hundred years the area was effectively controlled by local clans, such as the Armstrongs, who successfully resisted any attempt by the Scottish or English governments to impose their authority.
[src:darebase/anglo-scottish-border] In 1552 commissioners met to divide the land in two: Douglas of Drumlanrigg leading the Scots; Lord Wharton leading the English; the French ambassador acting as umpire.
[src:darebase/anglo-scottish-border] The Scots' Dike was built as the new frontier, with stones set up bearing the arms of England and of Scotland.
[src:darebase/anglo-scottish-border] Berwick is famous for its hesitation over whether it is part of Scotland or England.
[src:darebase/anglo-scottish-border] Berwickshire is in Scotland while the town is in England, although both Berwick and the lands up to the Firth of Forth belonged to the Kingdom of Northumbria in the Early Middle Ages.
[src:darebase/anglo-scottish-border] The town changed hands more than a dozen times before being finally taken by the English in 1482, though confusion continued for centuries.
[src:darebase/anglo-scottish-border] The Wales and Berwick Act 1746 clarified the status of Berwick as an English town.
[src:darebase/anglo-scottish-border] In the 1950s the artist Wendy Wood moved the border signs south to the middle of the River Tweed as a protest.
[src:darebase/anglo-scottish-border] In 2008 SNP MSP Christine Grahame made calls in the Scottish Parliament for Berwick to become part of Scotland again.
[src:darebase/anglo-scottish-border] At the River Tweed the border runs down the middle of the river, however between the villages of Wark and Cornhill the Scottish border comes south of the river to enclose a small riverside meadow of approximately 2 to 3 acres (about a hectare).
[src:darebase/anglo-scottish-border] It is said locally that every year the men of Coldstream (to the North of the river) would play mob football with the men of Wark (to the South of the river) at Ba, and the winning side would claim the Ba Green for their country.
[src:darebase/anglo-scottish-border] As Coldstream grew to have a larger population than Wark, the Coldstream men always defeated the Wark men at the game, and so the land became a permanent part of Scotland.
[src:darebase/anglo-scottish-border] It is a common misconception that Hadrian's Wall marks the Anglo-Scottish border.
[src:darebase/anglo-scottish-border] The wall lies entirely within England and has never formed this boundary.
[src:darebase/anglo-scottish-border] While in the west, at Bowness-on-Solway, it is less than 0.6 mi (1.0 km) south of the border with Scotland, in the east it is as much as 68 miles (109 km) away.
[src:darebase/anglo-scottish-border] For centuries the wall was the boundary between the Roman province of *Britannia* (to the south) and the Celtic lands of *Caledonia* (to the north).
[src:darebase/anglo-scottish-border] However *Britannia* occasionally extended as far north as the later Antonine Wall.
[src:darebase/anglo-scottish-border] Furthermore, to speak of England and Scotland at any time prior to the ninth century is anachronistic; such nations had no meaningful existence during the period of Roman rule.
[src:darebase/anglo-scottish-border] "Hadrian's Wall" is nonetheless sometimes used as an informal reference to the modern border, often semi-humorously.
[src:darebase/anglo-scottish-border] Cumbria and Northumberland have among the largest Scottish-born communities in the world outside Scotland.
[src:darebase/anglo-scottish-border] 16,628 Scottish-born people were residing in Cumbria in 2001 (3.41% of the county's population) and 11,435 Scottish-born people were residing in Northumberland (3.72% of the county's population); the overall percentage of Scottish-born people in England is 1.62%.
[src:darebase/anglo-scottish-border] Consequently, almost 9% of Scotland's population is English-born (459,486), with higher than average percentages of English-born people in both Dumfries & Galloway and the Scottish Borders council areas, respectively, reaching as high as 35% or higher English-born.
[src:darebase/ante-over] There are two teams, one on each side of the barrier.
[src:darebase/ante-over] A player on the team that starts with the ball throws the ball over the barrier to the other team, yelling some version of "Ante Over" to warn them that it has been thrown.
[src:darebase/ante-over] If the other team fails to catch the ball before it hits the ground, then they will yell "Ante Over" and throw it back.
[src:darebase/ante-over] If the team that is thrown to catches the ball, then the player holding the ball and this team run around the building and attempt to hit one of the members of the opposing team with the ball.
[src:darebase/ante-over] Players are "safe" if they succeed in running around the building without being hit.
[src:darebase/ante-over] If a player is hit, they then join the team of the player who hit them with the ball.
[src:darebase/ante-over] Play continues until one team has all of the players or just one is left.
[src:darebase/ante-over] In some versions of the game, if the ball bounces off the wall or rolls back without going over the roof, the thrower will yell "Pigs tail", to let the other team know the ball has been thrown but did not go over.
[src:darebase/ante-over] They then yell "Ante Over" again and make another attempt to throw the ball over the roof.
[src:darebase/ante-over] An indoor version of the game uses a curtain instead of a building.
[src:darebase/ante-over] Any tall obstacle that obscures the other team works for the game, although a gabled roof is part of traditional play.
[src:darebase/ante-over] When a building is used instead of a fence or some other narrow object, in some variations the ball must touch the other side of the roof.
[src:darebase/ante-over] Having the ball bounce this way can make it tougher for the other side to catch.
[src:darebase/ante-over] Some players even learn to finesse the ball rolling it up and over the roof.
[src:darebase/ante-over] When the barrier is a fence, or a similar obstacle that can be seen through, it is more difficult for the players to cheat as the other side can see if the ball does or does not hit the ground.
[src:darebase/ante-over] When it is a building, or other opaque barrier, players can sometimes stealth to the other side, catching the other team by surprise.
[src:darebase/ante-over] One rule has it that the opposing player can only be hit below the waist as a safety precaution like in dodge ball.
[src:darebase/ante-over] In some versions, players only have to run to the other side of the building to be "safe", while other versions require them to run all the way around the building.
[src:darebase/association-football] The objective of the game is to score more goals than the opposing team by moving the ball beyond the goal line into a rectangular-framed goal defended by the opponent.
[src:darebase/association-football] Traditionally, the game has been played over two 45-minute halves, for a total match time of 90 minutes.
[src:darebase/association-football] With an estimated 250 million players active in over 200 countries and territories, it is the world's most popular sport.
[src:darebase/association-football] Association football is played in accordance with the Laws of the Game, a set of rules that has been in effect since 1863 and maintained by the International Football Association Board (IFAB) since 1886.
[src:darebase/association-football] The game is played with a football that is 68–70 cm (27–28 in) in circumference.
[src:darebase/association-football] When the ball is in play, the players mainly use their feet, but may also use any other part of their body, except for their hands or arms, to control, strike, or pass the ball; the head, chest, and thighs are commonly used.
[src:darebase/association-football] Only the goalkeepers may use their hands and arms, but only within their own penalty area.
[src:darebase/association-football] Depending on the format of the competition, an equal number of goals scored may result in a draw being declared with 1 point awarded to each team, or the game may go into extra time or a penalty shoot-out.
[src:darebase/association-football] Internationally, association football is governed by FIFA.
[src:darebase/association-football] Under FIFA, there are six continental confederations: AFC, CAF, CONCACAF, CONMEBOL, OFC, and UEFA.
[src:darebase/association-football] National associations (e.g. the FA in England, U.S.
[src:darebase/association-football] Soccer in the United States, etc.) are responsible for managing the game in their own countries both professionally and at an amateur level, and coordinating competitions in accordance with the Laws of the Game.
[src:darebase/association-football] The most prestigious senior international competition is the FIFA World Cup.
[src:darebase/association-football] The men's World Cup is the most-viewed sporting event in the world, surpassing the Olympic Games.
[src:darebase/association-football] The most prestigious competition in European club football is the UEFA Champions League, which attracts an extensive television audience worldwide.
[src:darebase/association-football] The final of the men's Champions League is the most-watched annual sporting event in the world.
[src:darebase/association-football] Association football is part of a family of football games that emerged from various ball games played worldwide since antiquity.
[src:darebase/association-football] The word "association" in this term refers to the Football Association (the FA), founded in London in 1863, which published the first set of rules for the sport that same year.
[src:darebase/association-football] The term was coined to distinguish the type of football played in accordance with the FA rules from other types that were gaining popularity at the time, particularly rugby football.
[src:darebase/association-football] The term *soccer* comes from Oxford "-er" slang, which was prevalent at the University of Oxford in England from about 1875, and is thought to have been borrowed from the slang of Rugby School.
[src:darebase/association-football] Initially spelt *assoccer* (a shortening of "association"), it was later reduced to the modern spelling.
[src:darebase/association-football] Early alternative spellings included *socca* and *socker*.
[src:darebase/association-football] This form of slang also gave rise to *rugger* for rugby football, *fiver* and *tenner* for five pound and ten pound notes, and the now-archaic *footer* that was also a name for association football.
[src:darebase/association-football] A notable exception is New Zealand, where in the first two decades of the 21st century, under the influence of international television, "football" has been gaining prevalence, despite the dominance of other types of football, namely rugby union and rugby league.
[src:darebase/association-football] FIFA has stated that soccer originated in Britain, starting around the eighth century, and that no historical connection exists with any game played in antiquity outside Europe.
[src:darebase/association-football] The modern rules of association football are based on the mid-19th century efforts to standardise the widely varying forms of football played in the public schools of England.
[src:darebase/association-football] Kicking ball games arose independently multiple times across multiple cultures.
[src:darebase/association-football] The Chinese competitive game **cuju** (蹴鞠, literally "kickball"; also known as *tsu chu*) resembles modern association football as well as a mix of basketball and volleyball.
[src:darebase/association-football] This is the earliest form of a kicking game for which there is historical evidence.
[src:darebase/association-football] The game was first recorded as in exercise in the Zhan Guo Ce, a military history from the Han dynasty.
[src:darebase/association-football] **Cuju** players would pass the ball around, having to avoid it touching the ground at any point.
[src:darebase/association-football] It was then passed to a designated player, who attempted to kick it through the *fengliu yan*, a circular goal atop 10–11 meter poles.
[src:darebase/association-football] During the Han dynasty (206 BCE – 220 CE), **cuju** games were standardised and rules were established.
[src:darebase/association-football] The Silk Road facilitated the transmission of *cuju* outside of China, especially the form of the game popular in the Tang dynasty, the period when the inflatable ball was invented and replaced the stuffed ball.
[src:darebase/association-football] Other East Asian games include **kemari** in Japan and **chuk-guk** in Korea, both influenced by *cuju*.
[src:darebase/association-football] **Kemari** originated after the year 600 during the Asuka period.
[src:darebase/association-football] It was a ceremonial rather than a competitive game, and involved the kicking of a *mari*, a ball made of animal skin.
[src:darebase/association-football] In North America, *pasuckuakohowog* was a ball game played by the Algonquians; it was described as "almost identical to the kind of folk football being played in Europe at the same time, in which the ball was kicked through goals".
[src:darebase/association-football] In the Middle Ages, one notable game with similarities to modern football was *calcio storico fiorentino*, which originated in Florence, Italy.
[src:darebase/association-football] Another medieval sport that can be considered a form of early football is *la soule* (or *choule*), played in France from the 12th century, in which the ball was propelled by hands, feet, and sticks.
[src:darebase/association-football] As with pre-codified mob football, the antecedent of all modern football codes, these medieval games involved more handling of the ball than kicking it.
[src:darebase/association-football] The Cambridge rules, first drawn up at the University of Cambridge in 1848, were particularly influential in the development of subsequent codes, including association football.
[src:darebase/association-football] The Cambridge rules were written at Trinity College, Cambridge, at a meeting attended by representatives from Eton, Harrow, Rugby, Winchester, and Shrewsbury schools.
[src:darebase/association-football] During the 1850s, many clubs unconnected to schools or universities were formed throughout the English-speaking world to play various forms of football.
[src:darebase/association-football] Some came up with their own distinct codes of rules, most notably the Sheffield Football Club, formed by former public school pupils in 1857, which led to the formation of a Sheffield FA in 1867.
[src:darebase/association-football] In 1862, John Charles Thring of Uppingham School also devised an influential set of rules.
[src:darebase/association-football] These ongoing efforts contributed to the formation of the Football Association (the FA) in 1863, which first met on the morning of 26 October 1863 at the Freemasons' Tavern in Great Queen Street, London.
[src:darebase/association-football] The only school to be represented on this occasion was Charterhouse.
[src:darebase/association-football] The Freemasons' Tavern was the setting for five more meetings of the FA between October and December 1863; the English FA eventually issued the first comprehensive set of rules named Laws of the Game, forming modern football.
[src:darebase/association-football] The laws included bans on running with the ball in hand and hacking (kicking an opponent in the shins), tripping and holding.
[src:darebase/association-football] Eleven clubs, under the charge of FA secretary Ebenezer Cobb Morley, ratified the original thirteen laws of the game.
[src:darebase/association-football] The sticking point was hacking, which a twelfth club at the meeting, Blackheath FC, had wanted to keep, resulting in their withdrawal from the FA.
[src:darebase/association-football] Other English rugby clubs followed this lead and did not join the FA, and instead in 1871, along with Blackheath, formed the Rugby Football Union.
[src:darebase/association-football] The 1863 FA rules included handling of the ball by "marks" and the lack of a crossbar, making the game remarkably similar to Victorian rules football, which was being developed around the same time in Australia.
[src:darebase/association-football] The Sheffield FA played by its own rules until the 1870s, with the FA absorbing some of its rules until there was little difference between the games.
[src:darebase/association-football] The world's oldest football competition is the FA Cup, which was founded by the footballer and cricketer Charles W.
[src:darebase/association-football] Alcock, and has been contested by English teams since 1872.
[src:darebase/association-football] The first official international football match also took place in 1872, between Scotland and England in Glasgow, again at the instigation of Alcock.
[src:darebase/association-football] England is also home to the world's first football league, which was founded in Birmingham in 1888 by Aston Villa director William McGregor.
[src:darebase/association-football] The original format contained 12 clubs from the Midlands and Northern England.
[src:darebase/association-football] The Laws of the Game are determined by the International Football Association Board (IFAB).
[src:darebase/association-football] The board was formed in 1886 after a meeting in Manchester of the Football Association, the Scottish Football Association, the Football Association of Wales, and the Irish Football Association.
[src:darebase/association-football] FIFA, the international football body, was formed in Paris in 1904 and declared that they would adhere to the Laws of the Game of the Football Association.
[src:darebase/association-football] The growing popularity of the international game led to the admittance of FIFA representatives to the IFAB in 1913.
[src:darebase/association-football] The board consists of four representatives from FIFA and one representative from each of the four British associations.
[src:darebase/association-football] For most of the 20th century, Europe and South America were the dominant regions in association football.
[src:darebase/association-football] The FIFA World Cup, inaugurated in 1930, became the main stage for players of both continents to show their worth and the strength of their national teams.
[src:darebase/association-football] In the second half of the century, the European Cup and the Copa Libertadores were created, and the champions of these two club competitions would contest the Intercontinental Cup to prove which team was the best in the world.
[src:darebase/association-football] In the 21st century, South America has continued to produce some of the best footballers in the world, but its clubs have fallen behind the still dominant European clubs, which often sign the best players from Latin America and elsewhere.
[src:darebase/association-football] Meanwhile, football has improved in Africa, Asia, and North America, and nowadays, these regions are at least on equal grounds with South America in club football.
[src:darebase/association-football] Football is played at a professional level all over the world.
[src:darebase/association-football] Millions of people regularly go to football stadiums to follow their favourite teams, whilst billions more watch the game on television or on the internet.
[src:darebase/association-football] A very large number of people also play football at an amateur level.
[src:darebase/association-football] According to a survey conducted by FIFA published in 2001, over 240 million people from more than 200 countries regularly play football.
[src:darebase/association-football] Football has the highest global television audience in sport.
[src:darebase/association-football] In many parts of the world, football evokes great passions and plays an important role in the life of individual fans, local communities, and even nations.
[src:darebase/association-football] Ryszard Kapuściński says that Europeans who are polite, modest, or humble fall easily into rage when playing or watching football games.
[src:darebase/association-football] By contrast, football is widely considered to have been the final proximate cause for the Football War in June 1969 between El Salvador and Honduras.
[src:darebase/association-football] The sport also exacerbated tensions at the beginning of the Croatian War of Independence of the 1990s, when a match between Dinamo Zagreb and Red Star Belgrade degenerated into rioting in May 1990.
[src:darebase/association-football] The popularity of association football has been connected to identity fusion with replacement fandom collective identities.
[src:darebase/association-football] Women's association football has historically seen opposition, with national associations severely curbing its development and several outlawing it completely.
[src:darebase/association-football] Nevertheless, women have been playing football and similar games for as long as such games have existed.
[src:darebase/association-football] Frescoes from the Han dynasty (25–220 CE) depict female figures playing the ancient Chinese game *cuju*.
[src:darebase/association-football] There are also reports of annual football matches played by women in Midlothian, Scotland, during the 1790s.
[src:darebase/association-football] There is documented evidence of women's early involvement in association football.
[src:darebase/association-football] Informal matches between Scotland and England are reported to have taken place in 1881, but are not officially recognised by the respective football associations.
[src:darebase/association-football] The first women's match recorded by the Scottish Football Association took place in 1892 in Glasgow.
[src:darebase/association-football] In England, the first recorded game of football between women took place in 1895.
[src:darebase/association-football] The best-documented early European team was founded by activist Nettie Honeyball in England in 1894: the British Ladies' Football Club.
[src:darebase/association-football] Honeyball considered women's involvement in football as part of the emancipation movement.
[src:darebase/association-football] She and others like her paved the way for women's football.
[src:darebase/association-football] However, the women's game was frowned upon by the British football associations and continued without their support.
[src:darebase/association-football] It has been suggested that this was motivated by a perceived threat to the "masculinity" of the game.
[src:darebase/association-football] Women's football became popular on a large scale at the time of the First World War, when female employment in heavy industry spurred the growth of the game, much as it had done for men decades earlier.
[src:darebase/association-football] The most successful team of the era was Dick, Kerr Ladies F.C. of Preston, England.
[src:darebase/association-football] They played in one of the first women's international matches against a French XI team in 1920, and also made up most of the England team against a Scottish Ladies XI in the same year, winning 22–0.
[src:darebase/association-football] In the early 20th century, women's football in the United Kingdom was mostly associated with charity matches.
[src:darebase/association-football] Players and football writers have argued that this ban was, in fact, due to envy of the large crowds that women's matches attracted, and because the FA had no control over the money made from the women's game.
[src:darebase/association-football] The FA ban led to the formation of the short-lived English Ladies Football Association and play moved to rugby grounds.
[src:darebase/association-football] Women's football also faced bans in several other countries, notably in Brazil from 1941 to 1979, in France from 1941 to 1970, and in West Germany from 1955 to 1970.
[src:darebase/association-football] In spite of the resistance from governing bodies, British women continued to play football.
[src:darebase/association-football] Restrictions against female participation in the sport began to be reduced in the late 1960s and the 1970s.
[src:darebase/association-football] The Italian women's football league was established in 1968.
[src:darebase/association-football] In December 1969, the Women's Football Association was formed in England, with the sport eventually becoming the most prominent team sport for women in the United Kingdom.
[src:darebase/association-football] Two unofficial women's World Cups were organised by the FIEFF in 1970 and in 1971.
[src:darebase/association-football] Also in 1971, UEFA members voted to officially recognise women's football, while the Football Association rescinded the ban that prohibited women from playing on association members' pitches in England.
[src:darebase/association-football] The first Asian Women's Championship happened in 1975, initially without the approval of the AFC, but later recognised by them.
[src:darebase/association-football] Women's football still faces many struggles, but its worldwide growth has seen major competitions being launched at both the national and international levels, mirroring the men's competitions.
[src:darebase/association-football] The FIFA Women's World Cup was inaugurated in 1991: the first tournament was held in China, featuring 12 teams from the six confederations.
[src:darebase/association-football] The World Cup has been held every four years since; by 2019, it had expanded to 24 national teams, and 1.12 billion viewers watched the competition.
[src:darebase/association-football] Four years later, FIFA targeted the 32-team 2023 Women's World Cup at an audience of 2 billion, while more than 1.5 million tickets were sold, setting a Women's World Cup record.
[src:darebase/association-football] Women's football has been an Olympic event since 1996.
[src:darebase/association-football] North America is the dominant region in women's football, with the United States winning the most FIFA Women's World Cups and Olympic tournaments.
[src:darebase/association-football] Europe and Asia come second and third in terms of international success, and the women's game has been improving in South America.
[src:darebase/association-football] Association football is played in accordance with a set of rules known as the Laws of the Game.
[src:darebase/association-football] The game is played using a spherical ball of 68–70 cm (27–28 in) circumference, known as the *football* (or *soccer ball*).
[src:darebase/association-football] Two teams of eleven players each compete to get the ball into the other team's goal (between the posts and under the bar), thereby scoring a goal.
[src:darebase/association-football] There are situations where a goal can be disallowed, such as an offside call or a foul in the build-up to the goal.
[src:darebase/association-football] The team that has scored more goals at the end of the game is the winner; if both teams have scored an equal number of goals then the game is a draw.
[src:darebase/association-football] Each team is led by a captain who has only one official responsibility as mandated by the Laws of the Game: to represent their team in the coin toss before kick-off or penalty kicks.
[src:darebase/association-football] The primary law is that players other than goalkeepers may not deliberately handle the ball with their hands or arms during play, though they must use both their hands during a throw-in restart.
[src:darebase/association-football] Although players usually use their feet to move the ball around, they may use any part of their body (notably, "heading" with the forehead) other than their hands or arms.
[src:darebase/association-football] Within normal play, all players are free to play the ball in any direction and move throughout the pitch, though players may not pass to teammates who are in an offside position.
[src:darebase/association-football] During gameplay, players attempt to create goal-scoring opportunities through individual control of the ball, such as by dribbling, passing the ball to a teammate, and by taking shots at the goal, which is guarded by the opposing goalkeeper.
[src:darebase/association-football] Opposing players may try to regain control of the ball by intercepting a pass or through tackling the opponent in possession of the ball; however, physical contact between opponents is restricted.
[src:darebase/association-football] Football is generally a free-flowing game, with play stopping only when the ball has left the field of play or when play is stopped by the referee for an infringement of the rules.
[src:darebase/association-football] After a stoppage, play recommences with a specified restart.
[src:darebase/association-football] At a professional level, most matches produce only a few goals.
[src:darebase/association-football] For example, the 2022–23 season of the English Premier League produced an average of 2.85 goals per match.
[src:darebase/association-football] The Laws of the Game do not specify any player positions other than goalkeeper, but a number of specialised roles have evolved.
[src:darebase/association-football] Broadly, these include three main categories: strikers, or forwards, whose main task is to score goals; defenders, who specialise in preventing their opponents from scoring; and midfielders, who dispossess the opposition and keep possession of the ball to pass it to the forwards on their team.
[src:darebase/association-football] Players in these positions are referred to as outfield players, to distinguish them from the goalkeeper.
[src:darebase/association-football] These positions are further subdivided according to the area of the field in which the player spends the most time.
[src:darebase/association-football] For example, there are central defenders and left and right midfielders.
[src:darebase/association-football] The ten outfield players may be arranged in any combination.
[src:darebase/association-football] The number of players in each position determines the style of the team's play; more forwards and fewer defenders creates a more aggressive and offensive-minded game, while the reverse creates a slower, more defensive style of play.
[src:darebase/association-football] While players typically spend most of the game in a specific position, there are few restrictions on player movement, and players can switch positions at any time.
[src:darebase/association-football] The layout of a team's players is known as a *formation*.
[src:darebase/association-football] Defining the team's formation and tactics is usually the prerogative of the team's manager.
[src:darebase/association-football] There are seventeen laws in the official Laws of the Game, each containing a collection of stipulations and guidelines.
[src:darebase/association-football] The same laws are designed to apply to all levels of football for both sexes, although certain modifications for groups such as juniors, seniors and people with physical disabilities are permitted.
[src:darebase/association-football] The laws are often framed in broad terms, which allow flexibility in their application depending on the nature of the game.
[src:darebase/association-football] The Laws of the Game are published by FIFA, but are maintained by the IFAB.
[src:darebase/association-football] In addition to the seventeen laws, numerous IFAB decisions and other directives contribute to the regulation of association football.
[src:darebase/association-football] Within the United States, Major League Soccer used a distinct ruleset during the 1990s, and the NFHS and NCAA still use rulesets that are comparable to, but different from, the IFAB Laws.
[src:darebase/association-football] Each team consists of a maximum of eleven players (excluding substitutes), one of whom must be the goalkeeper.
[src:darebase/association-football] Competition rules may state a minimum number of players required to constitute a team, which is usually seven.
[src:darebase/association-football] Goalkeepers are the only players allowed to play the ball with their hands or arms, provided they do so within the penalty area in front of their own goal.
[src:darebase/association-football] Though there are a variety of positions in which the outfield (non-goalkeeper) players are strategically placed by a coach, these positions are not defined or required by the Laws.
[src:darebase/association-football] The basic equipment or *kit* players are required to wear includes a shirt, shorts, socks, footwear and adequate shin guards.
[src:darebase/association-football] Wearing an athletic supporter with protective cup is recommended for male players by medical experts and professionals.
[src:darebase/association-football] Headgear is not a required piece of equipment, but players may choose to wear it to protect themselves from head injury.
[src:darebase/association-football] Players are forbidden to wear or use anything that is dangerous to themselves or another player, such as jewellery or watches.
[src:darebase/association-football] The goalkeeper must wear clothing that is easily distinguishable from that worn by the other players and the match officials.
[src:darebase/association-football] A number of players may be replaced by substitutes during the course of the game.
[src:darebase/association-football] The maximum number of substitutions permitted in most competitive international and domestic league games is five in 90 minutes, with each team being allowed one more if the game should go into extra-time; the permitted number may vary in other competitions or in friendly matches.
[src:darebase/association-football] Common reasons for a substitution include injury, tiredness, ineffectiveness, a tactical switch, or timewasting at the end of a finely poised game.
[src:darebase/association-football] In standard adult matches, a player who has been substituted may not take further part in a match.
[src:darebase/association-football] IFAB recommends "that a match should not continue if there are fewer than seven players in either team".
[src:darebase/association-football] Any decision regarding points awarded for abandoned games is left to the individual football associations.
[src:darebase/association-football] A game is officiated by a referee, who has "full authority to enforce the Laws of the Game in connection with the match to which he has been appointed" (Law 5), and whose decisions are final.
[src:darebase/association-football] The referee is assisted by two assistant referees.
[src:darebase/association-football] In many high-level games there is also a fourth official who assists the referee and may replace another official should the need arise.
[src:darebase/association-football] Goal line technology is used to measure if the whole ball has crossed the goal-line thereby determining whether a goal has been scored or not; this was brought in to prevent controversy.
[src:darebase/association-football] Video assistant referees (VAR) have also been increasingly introduced in high-level matches to assist officials through video replays to correct clear and obvious mistakes.
[src:darebase/association-football] There are four types of calls that can be reviewed: mistaken identity in awarding a red or yellow card, goals and whether there was a violation during the build-up, direct red card decisions, and penalty decisions.
[src:darebase/association-football] The ball is spherical with a circumference of between 68 and 70 cm (27 and 28 in), a weight in the range of 410 to 450 g (14 to 16 oz), and a pressure between 0.6 and 1.1 standard atmospheres (8.5 and 15.6 pounds per square inch) at sea level.
[src:darebase/association-football] In the past the ball was made up of leather panels sewn together, with a latex bladder for pressurisation, but modern balls at all levels of the game are now synthetic.
[src:darebase/association-football] As the Laws were formulated in England, and were initially administered solely by the four British football associations within IFAB, the standard dimensions of a football pitch were originally expressed in imperial units.
[src:darebase/association-football] The Laws now express dimensions with approximate metric equivalents (followed by traditional units in brackets), though use of imperial units remains popular in English-speaking countries with a relatively recent history of metrication (or only partial metrication), such as Britain.
[src:darebase/association-football] The length of the pitch, or field, for international adult matches is in the range of 100–110 m (110–120 yd) and the width is in the range of 64–75 m (70–80 yd).
[src:darebase/association-football] Fields for non-international matches may be 90–120 m (100–130 yd) in length and 45–90 m (50–100 yd) in width, provided the pitch does not become square.
[src:darebase/association-football] In 2008, the IFAB initially approved a fixed size of 105 m (115 yd) long and 68 m (74 yd) wide as a standard pitch dimension for international matches; however, this decision was later put on hold and was never actually implemented.
[src:darebase/association-football] The longer boundary lines are *touchlines*, while the shorter boundaries (on which the goals are placed) are *goal lines*.
[src:darebase/association-football] A rectangular goal is positioned on each goal line, midway between the two touchlines.
[src:darebase/association-football] The inner edges of the vertical goal posts must be 7.32 m (24 ft) apart, and the lower edge of the horizontal crossbar supported by the goal posts must be 2.44 m (8 ft) above the ground.
[src:darebase/association-football] Nets are usually placed behind the goal, but are not required by the Laws.
[src:darebase/association-football] In front of the goal is the penalty area.
[src:darebase/association-football] This area is marked by the goal line, two lines starting on the goal line 16.5 m (18 yd) from the goalposts and extending 16.5 m (18 yd) into the pitch perpendicular to the goal line, and a line joining them.
[src:darebase/association-football] This area has a number of functions, the most prominent being to mark where the goalkeeper may handle the ball and where a penalty foul by a member of the defending team becomes punishable by a penalty kick.
[src:darebase/association-football] Other markings define the position of the ball or players at kick-offs, goal kicks, penalty kicks and corner kicks.
[src:darebase/association-football] A standard adult football match consists of two halves of 45 minutes each.
[src:darebase/association-football] Each half runs continuously, meaning that the clock is not stopped when the ball is out of play.
[src:darebase/association-football] There is usually a 15-minute half-time break between halves.
[src:darebase/association-football] The end of the match is known as full-time.
[src:darebase/association-football] The referee is the official timekeeper for the match, and may make an allowance for time lost through substitutions, injured players requiring attention, or other stoppages.
[src:darebase/association-football] This added time is called "additional time" in FIFA documents, but is most commonly referred to as *stoppage time* or *injury time*, while *lost time* can also be used as a synonym.
[src:darebase/association-football] The duration of stoppage time is at the sole discretion of the referee.
[src:darebase/association-football] Stoppage time does not fully compensate for the time in which the ball is out of play, and a 90-minute game typically involves about an hour of "effective playing time".
[src:darebase/association-football] The referee alone signals the end of the match.
[src:darebase/association-football] In matches where a fourth official is appointed, towards the end of the half, the referee signals how many minutes of stoppage time they intend to add.
[src:darebase/association-football] The fourth official then informs the players and spectators by holding up a board showing this number.
[src:darebase/association-football] The signalled stoppage time may be further extended by the referee.
[src:darebase/association-football] Added time was introduced because of an incident in 1891 during a match between Stoke and Aston Villa.
[src:darebase/association-football] Trailing 1–0 with two minutes remaining, Stoke were awarded a penalty kick.
[src:darebase/association-football] Villa's goalkeeper deliberately kicked the ball far out of play; by the time it was recovered, the clock had run out and the game was over, leaving Stoke unable to attempt the penalty.
[src:darebase/association-football] The same rule also states that the duration of either half is extended until a penalty kick to be taken or retaken is completed; thus, no game can end with an uncompleted penalty.
[src:darebase/association-football] Due to the relatively high ambient temperatures in some regions, cooling breaks for the players were introduced.
[src:darebase/association-football] Breaks could take place at the referee's discretion after the 30th minute of each half if the wet-bulb globe temperature exceeded 32 °C (90 °F); the breaks would last 3 minutes, with this time made up by an extended period of stoppage time at the end of the half.
[src:darebase/association-football] In league competitions, games may end in a draw.
[src:darebase/association-football] In knockout competitions where a winner is required, various methods may be employed to break such a deadlock; some competitions may invoke replays.
[src:darebase/association-football] A game tied at the end of regulation time may go into extra time, which consists of two further 15-minute periods.
[src:darebase/association-football] If the score is still tied after extra time, some competitions allow the use of penalty shoot-outs (previously known in the Laws of the Game as "kicks from the penalty mark") to determine which team will progress to the next stage of the tournament or be the champion.
[src:darebase/association-football] Goals scored during extra time periods count towards the final score of the game, but kicks from the penalty mark are only used to decide the team that progresses to the next part of the tournament, with goals scored in a penalty shoot-out not making up part of the final score.
[src:darebase/association-football] In competitions using two-legged matches, each team competes at home once, with an aggregate score from the two matches deciding which team progresses.
[src:darebase/association-football] Where aggregates are equal, the away goals rule may be used to determine the winners, in which case the winner is the team that scored the most goals in the leg they played away from home.
[src:darebase/association-football] If the result is still equal, extra time and potentially a penalty shoot-out are required.
[src:darebase/association-football] Under the Laws, the two basic states of play during a game are *ball in play* and *ball out of play*.
[src:darebase/association-football] From the beginning of each playing period with a kick-off until the end of the playing period, the ball is in play at all times, except when either the ball leaves the field of play, or play is stopped by the referee.
[src:darebase/association-football] Players are cautioned with a yellow card, and dismissed from the game with a red card.
[src:darebase/association-football] A foul occurs when a player commits an offence listed in the Laws of the Game while the ball is in play.
[src:darebase/association-football] The offences that constitute a foul are listed in Law 12.
[src:darebase/association-football] Handling the ball deliberately, tripping an opponent, or pushing an opponent, are examples of "penal fouls", punishable by a direct free kick or penalty kick depending on where the offence occurred.
[src:darebase/association-football] Other fouls are punishable by an indirect free kick.
[src:darebase/association-football] The referee may punish a player's or substitute's misconduct by a caution (yellow card) or dismissal (red card).
[src:darebase/association-football] A second yellow card in the same game leads to a red card, which results in a dismissal.
[src:darebase/association-football] A player given a yellow card is said to have been "booked", the referee writing the player's name in their official notebook.
[src:darebase/association-football] If a player has been dismissed, no substitute can be brought on in their place and the player may not participate in further play.
[src:darebase/association-football] Misconduct may occur at any time, and while the offences that constitute misconduct are listed, the definitions are broad.
[src:darebase/association-football] In particular, the offence of "unsporting behaviour" may be used to deal with most events that violate the spirit of the game, even if they are not listed as specific offences.
[src:darebase/association-football] A referee can show a yellow or red card to a player, substitute, substituted player, and to non-players such as managers and support staff.
[src:darebase/association-football] Rather than stopping play, the referee may allow play to continue if doing so will benefit the team against which an offence has been committed.
[src:darebase/association-football] This is known as "playing an advantage".
[src:darebase/association-football] The referee may "call back" play and penalise the original offence if the anticipated advantage does not ensue within "a few seconds".
[src:darebase/association-football] Even if an offence is not penalised due to advantage being played, the offender may still be sanctioned for misconduct at the next stoppage of play.
[src:darebase/association-football] The referee's decision in all on-pitch matters is considered final.
[src:darebase/association-football] The score of a match cannot be altered after the game, even if later evidence shows that decisions (including whether a goal was awarded or not) were incorrect.
[src:darebase/association-football] Along with the general administration of the sport, football associations and competition organisers also enforce good conduct in wider aspects of the game, dealing with issues such as comments to the press, clubs' financial management, doping, age fraud and match fixing.
[src:darebase/association-football] Most competitions enforce mandatory suspensions for players who are sent off in a game.
[src:darebase/association-football] Some on-field incidents, if considered very serious (such as allegations of racial abuse), may result in competitions deciding to impose heavier sanctions than those normally associated with a red card.
[src:darebase/association-football] Some associations allow for appeals against player suspensions incurred on-field if clubs feel a referee was incorrect or unduly harsh.
[src:darebase/association-football] Sanctions for such infractions may be levied on individuals or on clubs as a whole.
[src:darebase/association-football] Penalties may include fines, point deductions (in league competitions) or even expulsion from competitions.
[src:darebase/association-football] For example, the English Football League deduct 12 points from any team that enters financial administration.
[src:darebase/association-football] Among other administrative sanctions are penalties against game forfeiture.
[src:darebase/association-football] Teams that forfeit a game or are forfeited against are awarded a technical loss or win.
[src:darebase/association-football] The recognised international governing body of football (and associated games, such as futsal and beach soccer) is FIFA.
[src:darebase/association-football] The FIFA headquarters are located in Zürich, Switzerland.
[src:darebase/association-football] National associations (or national federations) oversee football within individual countries.
[src:darebase/association-football] 211 national associations are affiliated both with FIFA and with their respective continental confederations.
[src:darebase/association-football] Other national associations may be members of continental confederations but otherwise not participate in FIFA competitions.
[src:darebase/association-football] While FIFA is responsible for organising international competitions and enforcing most international regulations, the Laws of the Game are set by the IFAB, where each of the four UK associations holds one vote and FIFA collectively holds four votes.
[src:darebase/association-football] International competitions in association football principally consist of two varieties: competitions involving representative national teams or those involving clubs based in multiple nations and national leagues.
[src:darebase/association-football] *International football*, without qualification, most often refers to the former.
[src:darebase/association-football] In the case of international club competition, it is the country of origin of the clubs involved, not the nationalities of their players, that renders the competition international in nature.
[src:darebase/association-football] The major international competition in football and the most prestigious is the World Cup, organised by FIFA.
[src:darebase/association-football] This competition has taken place every four years since 1930, with the exception of the 1942 and 1946 tournaments, which were cancelled because of World War II.
[src:darebase/association-football] As of 2022, over 200 national teams compete in qualifying tournaments within the scope of continental confederations for a place in the finals.
[src:darebase/association-football] The finals tournament involved 32 national teams (expanding to 48 teams for the 2026 tournament) competing over a four-week period.
[src:darebase/association-football] The World Cup is the world's most widely viewed and most followed sporting event, with the 2022 tournament estimated to be watched by 5 billion people, more than 60% of the global population.
[src:darebase/association-football] The 1958 World Cup saw the emergence of Pelé as a global sporting star, a period that coincided with "the explosive spread of television, which massively amplified his presence everywhere".
[src:darebase/association-football] The current champions are Argentina, who won their third title at the 2022 tournament in Qatar.
[src:darebase/association-football] The FIFA Women's World Cup has been held every four years since 1991.
[src:darebase/association-football] Under the tournament's current format that was expanded in 2023, national teams vie for 31 slots in a three-year qualification phase, while the host nation's team enters automatically as the 32nd slot.
[src:darebase/association-football] The current champions are Spain, after winning their first title in the 2023 tournament.
[src:darebase/association-football] There has been a football tournament at every Summer Olympic Games since 1900, except at the 1932 games in Los Angeles when FIFA and the International Olympic Committee (IOC) had disagreed over the status of amateur players.
[src:darebase/association-football] Before the inception of the World Cup, the Olympics (especially during the 1920s) were the most prestigious international event.
[src:darebase/association-football] Originally, the tournament was for amateurs only.
[src:darebase/association-football] As professionalism spread around the world, the gap in quality between the World Cup and the Olympics widened.
[src:darebase/association-football] The countries that benefited most were the Soviet Bloc countries of Eastern Europe, where top athletes were state-sponsored while retaining their status as amateurs.
[src:darebase/association-football] Between 1948 and 1980, 23 out of 27 Olympic medals were won by Eastern Europe, with only Sweden (gold in 1948 and bronze in 1952), Denmark (bronze in 1948 and silver in 1960) and Japan (bronze in 1968) breaking their dominance.
[src:darebase/association-football] For the 1984 Los Angeles Games, the IOC allowed professional players to compete.
[src:darebase/association-football] Since 1992, male competitors must be under 23 years old, although since 1996, three players over the age of 23 have been allowed per squad.
[src:darebase/association-football] A women's tournament was added in 1996; in contrast to the men's event, full international sides without age restrictions play the women's Olympic tournament.
[src:darebase/association-football] After the World Cup, the most important international football competitions are the continental championships, which are organised by each continental confederation and contested between national teams.
[src:darebase/association-football] These are the European Championship (UEFA), the Copa América (CONMEBOL), the Africa Cup of Nations (CAF), the Asian Cup (AFC), the Gold Cup (CONCACAF) and the Nations Cup (OFC).
[src:darebase/association-football] These competitions are not strictly limited to members of the continental confederations, with guest teams from other continents sometimes invited to compete.
[src:darebase/association-football] The FIFA Confederations Cup was contested by the winners of all six continental championships, the current FIFA World Cup champions, and the country which was hosting the next World Cup.
[src:darebase/association-football] This was generally regarded as a warm-up tournament for the upcoming FIFA World Cup and did not carry the same prestige as the World Cup itself.
[src:darebase/association-football] The tournament was discontinued following the 2017 edition, with its calendar slot replaced by an expanded FIFA Club World Cup.
[src:darebase/association-football] The Finalissima was revived in 2022, and is contested between the Copa América and European Championship winners.
[src:darebase/association-football] The UEFA Nations League and the CONCACAF Nations League were introduced in the late 2010s to replace international friendlies during the two-year cycle between major tournaments.
[src:darebase/association-football] The most prestigious competitions in club football are the respective continental championships, which are generally contested between national champions, for example, the UEFA Champions League in Europe and the Copa Libertadores in South America.
[src:darebase/association-football] The winners of each continental competition contest the FIFA Intercontinental Cup, held annually, and the FIFA Club World Cup, held once every four years.
[src:darebase/association-football] In each country, football clubs are usually federated in associations or leagues that organise official tournaments among themselves, from which the champion of each country and the teams that will participate in international club tournaments emerge.
[src:darebase/association-football] There is no single system of competitions, and each national league organises them according to its own traditions.
[src:darebase/association-football] The governing bodies in each country operate league systems in a domestic season, normally comprising several divisions, in which the teams gain points throughout the season depending on results, usually three points for a win, one for a draw and zero for a defeat.
[src:darebase/association-football] Teams are put into tables, placed in order according to points accrued.
[src:darebase/association-football] In the Old World (Africa, Asia and Europe), it is common for each team to play every other team in its league at home and away in each season, in a round-robin tournament.
[src:darebase/association-football] At the end of a season, which typically runs from August to May, the top team is declared the champion.
[src:darebase/association-football] The top few teams may be promoted to a higher division, and one or more of the teams finishing at the bottom are relegated to a lower division.
[src:darebase/association-football] The teams finishing at the top of a country's league may also be eligible to play in international club competitions in the following season.
[src:darebase/association-football] Most countries supplement the league system with one or more "cup" competitions organised on a knock-out basis.
[src:darebase/association-football] These include the domestic cup, which may be open to all eligible teams in a country's league system—both professional and amateur—and is organised by the national federation.
[src:darebase/association-football] Some countries' top divisions feature highly-paid star players; in smaller countries, lower divisions, and many women's clubs, players may be part-timers with a second job, or amateurs.
[src:darebase/association-football] The top five European leagues – Premier League (England), Bundesliga (Germany), La Liga (Spain), Serie A (Italy), and Ligue 1 (France) – attract most of the world's best players and, during the 2006–07 season, each of these leagues had a total wage cost in excess of €600 million.
[src:darebase/association-football] These leagues also generated a combined €17.2 billion in revenue in the 2021–22 season from television contracts, matchday tickets, sponsorships, and other sources.
[src:darebase/association-football] In the 2022–23 season, clubs in Europe's "big five" leagues had an aggregate wage cost of €13 billion, with each league spending more than €1.8 billion in wages.
[src:darebase/association-football] In contrast, the combined revenue of these leagues was €19.6 billion.
[src:darebase/association-football] Variants of association football have been codified for teams of reduced size, such as five-a-side football; for non-traditional playing environments, including beach soccer, futsal and indoor soccer; and for athletes with disabilities (Paralympic football).
[src:darebase/association-football] Street football can be played with only minimal equipment – a basic game can be played on almost any open area of reasonable size with just a ball made from almost any material and items to mark the positions of the goalposts.
[src:darebase/association-football] Such informal games can have team sizes that vary from eleven-a-side, can use a limited or modified subset of the official rules, and can be self-officiated by the players.
[src:darebase/atya-patya] The national governed body of the sport is the "Atya Patya Federation of India".
[src:darebase/atya-patya] The ministry of Youth Affairs and Sports, government of India, lists the federation amongst its list of recognised federation for the year 2013.
[src:darebase/atya-patya] The federation is headquartered in Nagpur.
[src:darebase/atya-patya] The first south Asian Atya patya Championship was held in Bhutan in June, 2013.
[src:darebase/atya-patya] Some of the alternative names for atya-patya are Killithattu/Klithatu (in Tamil Nadu), Kili Thadthu (in Sri Lanka), Wanjh Wati (in Sindh), Gallery, Sur-pati, Lon-pati, Darya-banth, saragari, saramani, tilli, uppinat, uppupatti, choupal pati, panchwati, and chikka.
[src:darebase/atya-patya] A related Bengali game is Dari Bandha/Dariabandha, in which the attacking team is considered to be "stealing salt" by making it up the court and then "taking the salt back" to the start of the court.
[src:darebase/atya-patya] In Southeast Asia, similar games can be found, such as Galah Panjang/Toi/Tui/Belon Acah in Malaysia, Gobak Sodor/Galah Asin in Indonesia, Htote See Toe in Myanmar, and Patintero in the Philippines.
[src:darebase/atya-patya] Due to the history of Dutch colonialism in the region, the game was also played by Dutch children.
[src:darebase/atya-patya] Atya-patya was mentioned in the Natṟiṇai, which was written before 300 AD.
[src:darebase/atya-patya] It was used as combat practice by soldiers in the Chola dynasty.
[src:darebase/atya-patya] The playing field is a rectangular court, with a central lane or "trench" 89 feet and 1 inch (27.15 m) long marked lengthwise down the middle of the court.
[src:darebase/atya-patya] Nine additional trenches, each 23 feet and 1 inch (7.03 m) long, are drawn on the court perpendicular to the central trench and 11 feet (3.4 m) away from each other, from one end of the court to the other.
[src:darebase/atya-patya] The game is played in four innings (turns), with each inning lasting for seven minutes, and the teams alternating attacking and defending roles in each inning.
[src:darebase/atya-patya] Before each inning, the defensive team places one player in each of the trenches.
[src:darebase/atya-patya] A batch of four players on the attacking team, who are referred to as "assailants", line up at one end of the court, in the area in front of the front trench.
[src:darebase/atya-patya] The goal of the assailants is to score by crossing each trench without being eliminated; the total number of points scored in an inning by the attacking team is equal to the number of trenches crossed by their furthest-advancing assailant.
[src:darebase/atya-patya] If an assailant is touched by a defender (and the defender commits no faults, such as stepping out of their trench, or lifting a foot at or immediately after the time of tagging the assailant), then the assailant is "out", and must leave the court.
[src:darebase/atya-patya] The assailant is also out if they step out of the field while failing to keep any part of their body grounded within the field.
[src:darebase/atya-patya] If an assailant crosses all nine trenches, they may say the word "Tond", which compels the defenders to turn around, allowing the assailant to now attempt to re-cross the nine trenches in the opposite direction.
[src:darebase/atya-patya] Atya-patya matches are decided on a best-of-three basis.
[src:darebase/atya-patya] The defender in the front trench is known as a "grenadier" or "sur", and is able to run in either the front trench or the central trench.
[src:darebase/atya-patya] Grenadiers are allowed to commit any fault other than a foot fault or hand fault where part of their body goes outside of their trench.
[src:darebase/atya-patya] Special rules apply when two or more assailants are encircled by a regular defender and a grenadier, which is known as a "ring".
[src:darebase/atya-patya] The national level Atya Patya tournament for 2013 was held at Bhatkal in Karnataka.
[src:darebase/atya-patya] Represented by 22 states & Union Territories, the event was organized jointly by Karnataka Atya Patya association Davangere and Bhatkal Atya Patya association.
[src:darebase/atya-patya] The president of Puducherry Atya patya Association, Selvan refuted accusations levelled by Anbhagan, Member of Legislative Assembly, Puducherry, that Atya patya certificates were issued to take benefit of quota available to sports persons, in seats at medical colleges.
[src:darebase/atya-patya] He stated that the sport was registered in 22 states of India including in Tamil Nadu.
[src:darebase/aunt-sally] It was suggested by James Redding Ware that the term was based on a blackface doll, itself inspired by a low-life character named "Black Sal," which appeared in an 1821 novel entitled *Life in London* by Pierce Egan, a contemporary of Charles Dickens.
[src:darebase/aunt-sally] The game dates back to the 17th century, although the name "Aunt Sally" may have been a later addition.
[src:darebase/aunt-sally] It was traditionally played in central English pubs and fairgrounds.
[src:darebase/aunt-sally] An Aunt Sally was originally the modelled head of an old woman with a clay pipe in her mouth; the object was for players to throw sticks at the head in order to break the pipe.
[src:darebase/aunt-sally] The target has also been a puppet, live person, or a simple ball on a stick.
[src:darebase/aunt-sally] There are also other theories of how the game started.
[src:darebase/aunt-sally] One such theory is that a live cockerel was placed on the stick, and people would throw sticks at it.
[src:darebase/aunt-sally] Whoever killed it won the game and took home the chicken.
[src:darebase/aunt-sally] Another theory is that in Port Meadow in Oxfordshire, at the time of the English Civil War, the Cavaliers (soldiers loyal to King Charles I) were bored and formed a game with sticks and makeshift materials similar to the game as understood today.
[src:darebase/aunt-sally] The game has also been played outside of the UK; picnic attendees were reported to play Aunt Sally in Australia in the 1880s.
[src:darebase/aunt-sally] Today, the game of Aunt Sally is still played as a pub game in Berkshire, Buckinghamshire, Gloucestershire, Oxfordshire, Northamptonshire and Warwickshire.
[src:darebase/aunt-sally] In 2011 the inaugural Aunt Sally Singles World Championship took place at the Charlbury Beer Festival in Charlbury, West Oxfordshire.
[src:darebase/aunt-sally] Among the attendees was Prime Minister David Cameron.
[src:darebase/aunt-sally] The tournament has continued there annually ever since.
[src:darebase/aunt-sally] On 24 August 2019, the first world championship for Aunt Sally pairs was held in the Bull, Launton, Oxfordshire, and was won by the pub team from The Bell, Bicester.
[src:darebase/aunt-sally] Darren Moore and Billy Craig were the winners.
[src:darebase/aunt-sally] Runners-up were Aimee Sheehan and Christopher Hulme.
[src:darebase/aunt-sally] The game bears some resemblance to a coconut shy or skittles but with teams.
[src:darebase/aunt-sally] Each team consists of eight players or five players depending on the local league.
[src:darebase/aunt-sally] The ball is on a short plinth about 4 to 6 inches (100 to 150 mm) high by 3 inches (75 mm) diameter, known as the "dolly", which is placed on a dog-legged metal spike (the swivel) about 30 to 40 inches (750 mm to 1000 mm) high.
[src:darebase/aunt-sally] Players throw sticks or short battens, about 18 by 2 inches (450 x 50 mm) at the dolly, from ten yards away, trying to knock it off without hitting the spike.
[src:darebase/aunt-sally] Successfully hitting the dolly off is known as a "doll"; however, if the spike is hit first, then the score does not count and is called an "iron".
[src:darebase/aunt-sally] A zero score (after 6 sticks are thrown) is known as a "blob" and marked with an X on the scoreboard.
[src:darebase/aunt-sally] If all legs are a blob the person is a "blobber".
[src:darebase/australian-handball] Australian handball is a ball sport played in an enclosed court in which players strike a small ball directly against a front wall using their hands rather than a racquet.
[src:darebase/australian-handball] Unlike similar court sports such as squash, no racket or other equipment is used; the ball is struck with the palm or fist.
[src:darebase/australian-handball] Play begins with a serve, in which the ball is hit directly against the front wall without first bouncing on the ground.
[src:darebase/australian-handball] The opposing player must return the ball before it bounces twice.
[src:darebase/australian-handball] During play, the ball may also rebound from side walls either before or after striking the front wall; however, after a player strikes the ball, it must contact the front wall before touching the ground.
[src:darebase/australian-handball] The game can be played in singles or doubles formats on courts with one, three, or four walls.
[src:darebase/australian-handball] The three-wall court is the most common configuration used for organized play.
[src:darebase/australian-handball] Courts used for the sport are found at a number of educational institutions and sporting facilities in Australia, including several private schools and colleges.
[src:darebase/australian-handball] Although its formal beginnings in Australia date from 1923, it has been played in some capacity or another since the 19th century.
[src:darebase/australian-handball] The first Australian Handball court was built by Melbourne hotel-keeper, Michael Lynch, in 1847.
[src:darebase/australian-handball] Its early development has been attributed to the work of Christian Brothers' Colleges.
[src:darebase/australian-handball] Handball was very strongly promoted among the students at Christian Brothers' Colleges, driven by the Brothers' view that handball "affords an excellent preparatory training for football, as it calls into play all the resources of the physical man".
[src:darebase/australian-handball] Over most of its history, its primary play has been in Victoria, South Australia, and New South Wales.
[src:darebase/australian-handball] By 1970, there were about 1,000 players registered within the New South Wales, Victorian, and South Australian state associations.
[src:darebase/australian-handball] For many decades, the Australian Handball Council has held almost annual national championships, and each state has held its own state titles.
[src:darebase/australian-handball] During the 1950s and 1960s, both the Australian Singles Schoolboys Handball Championships and the Australian Doubles Schoolboys Handball Championships were held on a regular basis.
[src:darebase/australian-handball] Many great champions participated in these schoolboy rivalries.
[src:darebase/australian-handball] Additionally, over many decades Australians have made regular appearances at the World Junior and World Senior Titles.
[src:darebase/australian-handball] Within Australia, of more recent decades, the chief rivalries have been between Victoria and South Australia.
[src:darebase/australian-handball] For the past three decades, the states have generally competed at a 'midpoint' venue, often Warrnambool, Victoria, over one weekend annually, for the national handball championships.
[src:darebase/australian-handball] In some areas, modern changes to school venues have meant the disappearance of the school's traditional handball courts, making it harder on handballers to access the game.
[src:darebase/australian-handball] The game is nationally run by the Australian Handball Council, formed in 1928, of which the current executive director is Jim Kiley, and the Secretary/Treasurer is Greg Hay.
[src:darebase/australian-handball] A few highly respected names in the game's history include multiple national champions Jim Flattery, Tim Tucker, and George Macris in the first half of the 20th century, and John Hughes of Victoria, Paul Fallon of NSW , Lou Ravesi of SA, and Vic DeLuzio and Geoff Walsh of Victoria, in the 2nd half.
[src:darebase/darebase] The size of the game field typically ranges from between that of a basketball court and about half the size of a football or soccer field.
[src:darebase/darebase] Each base belongs to the team that starts on that side and if the distance between the bases is longer than the average player is able to sprint, game play will begin to suffer.
[src:darebase/darebase] Effective game play can be achieved with as few as ten players and up to a hundred or more just as long as the game field and base lines are large enough to accommodate them.
[src:darebase/darebase] Darebase is popular in many areas of the United States as a recess game and at summer camps in part because of its simplicity, flexibility, and capacity to accommodate players of varying age and ability, as well as its potential for rapid and dynamic play even when teams are evenly matched.
[src:darebase/darebase] The game appears to have been known originally as "bars", "base" or "prisoners' bars".
[src:darebase/darebase] One of the earliest known references dates from the early 14th century, when King Edward III of England issued an order prohibiting "*barres*" from being played in the avenues of the Palace of Westminster.
[src:darebase/darebase] An early description of *Prisoner's Base*, entitled *De Ludo Gjitûcum Chudûni*, was written by Thomas Hyde who described it as a game from Mesopotamia.
[src:darebase/darebase] It was published in 1767 under the name *Prison-Base* and *Prisoners Base* in Gregory Sharpe's book *Syntagma dissertationum quas olim Thomas Hyde S.T.P. separatim edidit*.
[src:darebase/darebase] In 1796, Hyde's playing rules have been extensively translated into German and published in Germany under the name *Das Foppen und Fangen.
[src:darebase/darebase] Prisonners-Base* in the game book *Spiele zur Übung und Erholung des Körpers und Geistes* by Johann Christoph Friedrich GutsMuths.
[src:darebase/darebase] The alternative name "Chevy Chace" is derived from the traditional "Ballad of Chevy Chase", and the semi-legendary battle on the Anglo-Scottish border that it supposedly commemorates.
[src:darebase/darebase] Sims in 1906 described Chevy Chace as "a form of prisoners' base in which one unit of a 'side' is captured and held to ransom until a comrade rescues him".
[src:darebase/darebase] A street scene photographed in Blue Eye, Missouri in c.1916 was allegedly taken during a local game of darebase.
[src:darebase/darebase] In India, a similar game is known as Gella-Chutt (transl.
[src:darebase/darebase] "the king escaped") or *Sita Udhar* ("Sita is over there"), in which the game represents the struggle of a king's guards to rescue him, or represents the scene from the Ramayana in which Sita is saved from the demons of Lanka.
[src:darebase/darebase] Darebase can be won in four different ways.
[src:darebase/darebase] First, by capturing all of the opposing team's players.
[src:darebase/darebase] Second, by occupying the opposing team's base when the opposing team is absent from their base.
[src:darebase/darebase] Third, by having captured more of the opposing team's players when time has run out, though the game does not require a time limit in order to be played.
[src:darebase/darebase] One variation of darebase, in which bases represent islands in the no-man's, allow victory to be achieved when one player makes the ultimate dare by running all the way around the opposing team's base and back into their own without being tagged by the other team.
[src:darebase/darebase] For a player to be captured they must be tagged by an opposing team's player that has entered no-man's land after that player, a condition commonly referred to as being "fresher." Players can return to their base line at any time to become fresher.
[src:darebase/darebase] If they are able, they may also use the opposing team's base line to become "fresher" and to become safe from capture.
[src:darebase/darebase] In Hawaii, the concept of "fresher" is referred to as "mana" or power.
[src:darebase/darebase] One's mana decreases over time and can be recharged by returning to one's base.
[src:darebase/darebase] In another variation, a team member may transfer mana to another player, though this may lead to confusion in games with large numbers of players.
[src:darebase/darebase] Game play typically starts with players engaging in a series of feints, or dares.
[src:darebase/darebase] Dares take the form of a player approaching the opposite base and baiting opposing players into giving chase.
[src:darebase/darebase] The pursuer is then drawn towards the enemy line.
[src:darebase/darebase] The pursued must assess where their personal point-of-no-return lies based on a combination of factors: their own speed and agility, the speed of their pursuer, and the speed of anyone backing them up.
[src:darebase/darebase] Being able to get as close as possible to this point without crossing it affords the greatest tactical advantage and results in the most dynamic play.
[src:darebase/darebase] If players on both teams cautiously avoid the point-of-no-return and thus do not invite pursuit, a condition of stalemate may result.
[src:darebase/darebase] If a player's dare is accepted, the pursuer will often cross their own point-of-no-return in an attempt to capture their quarry.
[src:darebase/darebase] This usually results in one or more players from the team of the pursued crossing their lines to intercept the pursuer.
[src:darebase/darebase] Any time members of one team cross their own line, the opposing team tends to respond with fresher players.
[src:darebase/darebase] This causes waves of alternating advantage to converge in the center of the field.
[src:darebase/darebase] When a pursuer is faced with a fresher opponent, he or she may choose to retreat either to their own line or to the position of a fresher teammate, attempt to complete the capture, or attempt to cross the opposing team's base line at an undefended point.
[src:darebase/darebase] Being able to cross the opposing team's base line affords a strong tactical advantage analogous to a flanking maneuver.
[src:darebase/darebase] A player who has achieved this position is sometimes referred to as a spy.
[src:darebase/darebase] A spy is able to chase opposing players from behind and must be guarded closely, effectively neutralizing one or more players in the process.
[src:darebase/darebase] A spy may choose to remain in place as a continuous threat.
[src:darebase/darebase] However, it is rare for such a player to remain in place for very long after they have rested.
[src:darebase/darebase] A player capable of crossing the opponent's line, especially early in the game, will almost always use their advantage to attempt to capture one of the opposing team's fastest players.
[src:darebase/darebase] This fact only serves to enhance the degree to which spies are treated with caution.
[src:darebase/darebase] When one player captures another player, both players become immediately inactive or neutral until the captor finishes escorting the captured player to jail.
[src:darebase/darebase] Each team's jail is located in a corner of the field and is represented by a specific marked point on the base line such as a field cone or an article of clothing.
[src:darebase/darebase] The jailed player must be in physical contact with the jail point to be eligible for rescue.
[src:darebase/darebase] They may stretch out or lay down to increase their cross section.
[src:darebase/darebase] If an additional player is captured and brought to jail, that player must be in physical contact with the first player and may also stretch out.
[src:darebase/darebase] As this chain of jailed players gets longer its end gets closer to its players base line.
[src:darebase/darebase] This makes it easier for would-be rescuers to reach the line without being caught themselves.
[src:darebase/darebase] To free players from jail, a rescuer must tag the jailed player.
[src:darebase/darebase] There are several variations of darebase that hinge on different rules for freeing captured players from jail.
[src:darebase/darebase] In one variation, only one person can be freed at a time: whichever player has been in jail the longest.
[src:darebase/darebase] In this variation, the most recently captured player joins the line at the point of the jail while the players that have been in jail the longer move towards the other end of the line.
[src:darebase/darebase] The most senior prisoner must be tagged in order to be freed.
[src:darebase/darebase] Another variation allows all players to be freed if any of the jailed players are tagged.
[src:darebase/darebase] Yet another variation is actually a hybrid of the two above.
[src:darebase/darebase] To free all players, the rescuer must tag the point of the jail.
[src:darebase/darebase] Alternately, a rescuer is able to free just the most senior prisoner who is at the end of the line by tagging them directly.
[src:darebase/darebase] Once a rescuer has freed one or more prisoners they and those who are freed are immune to capture until they return to their team's base.
[src:darebase/darebase] Darebase provides several key roles that players typically occupy with very little discussion or leadership.
[src:darebase/darebase] Some players choose to place themselves out front, attempting to draw chase from the opposing team's fastest players.
[src:darebase/darebase] This dueling eventually results in one team's fastest player(s) being captured, or in gaining the advantage of crossing the other team's base line.
[src:darebase/darebase] Other players, whose personal point-of-no-return is closer to their home base, naturally employ more defensive tactics such as guarding the line, the jail, or shadowing spies.
[src:darebase/darebase] References to the game are found in a range of early modern English literary works, including those of Christopher Marlowe, Edmund Spenser, Richard Brome, and Michael Drayton.
[src:darebase/darebase] Anstey's comic novel *Vice Versa* (1882), the boys at Dr Grimstone's boarding school are required to play a game called "chevy" – "so called from the engagement famed in ballad and history", and said to be "commonly known as 'prisoners' base'".
[src:darebase/darebase] Marcel Proust refers to playing it on the Champs Elysées in Volume one of In Search of Lost Time.
